               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "### Prerequisites\n\nThis text begins to explore the idea of sharing (or dividing) by four in nature. We recommend reviewing the previous texts in this chapter (<htcite0>) before continuing.",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "2fd2e872-c5d8-4f1b-91dc-97df40597c4e",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Evolution of Knowledge (Atom)",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_introduction",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Introduction\n\nGroups of four have been used by humanity for millennia.\nSome of these groups are still in use today, while others have been left behind as we have gained more knowledge about how nature works.\n\nGiven this context, let’s begin with a reflection:",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 1: Grouping</b><br /><br />Stop and look around you.<br /><br />How many groups of four objects do you have nearby?<br /><br />Could there be an internal grouping among them that you haven’t yet identified?</div></div></center>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_body",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Our Body\n\nThe human body is one single entity, but we can understand it by parts, as shown in **Figure 1**:",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"desc\"><img src=\"images/HistoryTracers/HTHumanBody.jpg\" id=\"imgHHB\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgHHB', '0%')\" class=\"imgcenter\"/><b>Figure 1</b>: Human Body. © History Tracers. <span id=\"htImgCopyright\"></span>.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "#### Limbs\n\nOne way to classify the body’s limbs (regions 6, 7, 8, and 9) is to divide them into two groups:\n- **Upper limbs**: include the hands and arms (regions 6 and 7);\n- **Lower limbs**: include the legs and feet (regions 8 and 9).\n\nAlthough this may seem like a good initial separation, we must remember that we have already seen that our body can also be classified into two different sides (<htcite0>). As a result, we can make a new classification:\n- **Right upper limb**: right hand and arm;\n- **Left upper limb**: left hand and arm;\n- **Right lower limb**: right leg and foot;\n- **Left lower limb**: left leg and foot.",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "112e532d-e8af-40d6-b1b5-527978ee42f3",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Two sides",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "Dividing the limbs into more than just two parts (upper and lower) allows us to describe the body more precisely, since we can specify exactly which limb we are referring to.\n\nThis precision in describing our body can also be extended to objects, as we will see next.",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_objects",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Objects\n\nHuman beings are not the only animals whose body organization can be associated with the number four. When we observe nature, we notice that animals that move on four legs — known as quadrupeds — can also be classified according to the position of their limbs on the body.",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"desc\"><img id=\"catsCirusUrraca\" src=\"images/HistoryTracers/CatsCirusUrraca.jpg\" class=\"imgcenter\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('catsCirusUrraca', '0%')\" /><b>Figure 2</b>: Editors’ cats.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "By observing **Figure 1 and 2**, we can conclude that if a person standing upright bends forward and places their hands on the ground, they will assume a position similar to that of the cats in **Figure 2**.\n\nThis fact leads us to a reflection:",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 2: Equality</b><br /><br />Both the human body and that of quadrupeds can be divided into groups of four.<br /><br />Can you list other characteristics we share with cats?<br /><br />What might these similarities be telling us?</div></div></center>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "To help guide your reflection, remember that in the first moments of our lives, we do not walk — before taking our first steps, we crawl.\n\nIt is possible that observing these behaviors inspired our species to build tables and altars like those in **Slide 1**.",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><div class=\"htSlides\"></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"desc\"><b>Slide 1</b>: Images of Altar Q at the archaeological site of Copán, Honduras. Photo taken during a visit on <htdate0>.<br />The names of the kings (<i>ajawob</i>) are detailed in the work of Anastasia Hutnick (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('85c2d88c-6ad8-4858-95f8-0f157c49bf07'); return false;\">Hutnick, Anastasia, <htdate1>, pp. 18, 35 - 67.</a>).<br />The slide's source code was inspired by a template from <a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('cf7adc72-d340-412e-8d48-953ac64cb670'); return false;\">W3Schools</a>.</p>",
